---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "iShares Core S&P 500 ETF (IVV) Dividend Analysis & Expense Ratio",
  description: "Are you losing your market returns to high management fees? We reveal the core metrics and true costs behind one of the world's most popular index funds.",
  category: "study",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "iShares Core S&P 500 ETF (IVV) Dividend Analysis & Expense Ratio",
      "description": meta.description,
      "datePublished": meta.published,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Fundamentals"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the iShares Core S&P 500 ETF IVV expense ratio in 2025?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The iShares Core S&P 500 ETF (IVV) expense ratio in 2025 remains ultra-low at just 0.03%, meaning investors pay only $3 annually for every $10,000 invested."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does the iShares Core S&P 500 ETF IVV pay a dividend?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, IVV pays a dividend derived from the underlying companies in the S&P 500 index. The yield generally tracks the broad market, typically hovering around 1.1% to 1.3%."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How often are dividends paid on IVV?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "IVV distributes its dividends to shareholders on a quarterly basis, usually in March, June, September, and December."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is IVV better than SPY for expense ratio?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, IVV's expense ratio of 0.03% is lower than SPY's expense ratio of 0.09%, making IVV slightly more cost-effective for long-term buy-and-hold investors."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What companies are in the IVV ETF?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "IVV holds the same 500 large-cap U.S. companies that make up the S&P 500 Index, including major technology, healthcare, and financial sector leaders."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/ishares-core-sp-500-etf-ivv-expense-ratio" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content container">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>iShares Core S&P 500 ETF (IVV) Analysis</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Evaluating the true cost of ownership, dividend payouts, and long-term performance potential of IVV.</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>The True Cost of Market Exposure</h2>
      <p>For investors searching for the "ishares core s&p 500 etf ivv expense ratio", the focus is rightly on cost. IVV is BlackRock's flagship S&P 500 index fund, designed to provide long-term capital growth by mirroring the performance of large-capitalization U.S. equities. Because index funds are commodities, the defining factor between them often comes down to fees.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Key IVV Metrics</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Current Dividend Yield:</strong> ~1.17%</li>
          <li><strong>Expense Ratio:</strong> 0.03%</li>
          <li><strong>Trailing P/E Ratio:</strong> 26.54</li>
          <li><strong>Assets Under Management (AUM):</strong> ~$750 Billion</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <p>At 0.03%, the "ishares core s&p 500 etf ivv expense ratio 2025" remains one of the lowest in the industry. This ultra-low fee structure allows investors to capture virtually all of the index's total return, making it a staple for retirement accounts and long-term wealth building.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>5-Year Dividend History</h2>
      <p>While IVV is not a dedicated high-yield fund, it does pass through the dividends paid by the 500 companies within its portfolio. Because the S&P 500 generally grows its earnings over time, the absolute dollar amount of the dividend paid by IVV tends to grow annually, even if the percentage yield remains relatively stable due to stock price appreciation.</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Ex-Dividend Date</th>
            <th>Amount ($)</th>
            <th>Frequency</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Dec 16, 2025</td>
            <td>2.414</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Sep 16, 2025</td>
            <td>1.995</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Jun 16, 2025</td>
            <td>1.867</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Mar 18, 2025</td>
            <td>1.765</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Dec 17, 2024</td>
            <td>2.134</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><em>Note: Dividend amounts reflect the per-share payouts, showing a consistent pattern of passing through corporate earnings to shareholders.</em></p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Dividend Growth Rate Analysis</h2>
      <p>The dividend growth of IVV mirrors the aggregate dividend growth of the S&P 500. Over the past decade, this has averaged roughly 6% to 8% annually. This reliable growth acts as a natural hedge against inflation, ensuring that the purchasing power of the income generated by the portfolio is maintained over long horizons.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Comparison to Category Average</h2>
      <p>When comparing IVV to its closest competitors—namely SPY (State Street) and VOO (Vanguard)—the differences are marginal but important. IVV's 0.03% expense ratio matches VOO and undercuts SPY's 0.09%. For institutional traders needing immense liquidity, SPY is often preferred. But for retail investors building a long-term passive portfolio, IVV and VOO are the optimal choices.</p>
      <p>If you are looking for higher immediate income rather than broad market growth, you might compare IVV's ~1.17% yield against a dedicated dividend ETF, such as the one covered in our <a href="/spyd-expense-ratio-2024">SPYD Analysis</a> or explore extreme high-yield strategies in our <a href="/high-yield-dividend-etf-passive-income">HIGH ETF review</a>.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Interactive Cost & Dividend Reinvestment Calculator</h2>
      <p>See exactly how much IVV's low expense ratio saves you, and project your dividend income based on your position size.</p>

      <div class="card" id="calcContainer" data-initialized="false">
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="shares" style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">Shares Owned:</label>
          <input type="number" id="shares" value="100" min="1" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary);" />
        </div>
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="sharePrice" style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">Share Price ($):</label>
          <input type="number" id="sharePrice" value="535.00" step="0.01" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary);" />
        </div>
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="yield" style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">Dividend Yield (%):</label>
          <input type="number" id="yield" value="1.17" step="0.01" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary);" />
        </div>
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="expRatio" style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">IVV Expense Ratio (%):</label>
          <input type="number" id="expRatio" value="0.03" step="0.01" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary);" />
        </div>
        <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color);">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Total Investment Value: <span id="totalValue" style="color: var(--text-primary); font-size: 1.1rem;">$53,500.00</span></h4>
          <h4 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Annual Expense Fee: <span id="feeAmount" style="color: #e74c3c; font-size: 1.1rem;">-$16.05</span></h4>
          <h4 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Net Annual Dividend Income: <span id="netIncome" style="color: var(--accent-color); font-size: 1.25rem;">$609.90</span></h4>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the iShares Core S&P 500 ETF IVV expense ratio in 2025?</summary>
        <p>The iShares Core S&P 500 ETF (IVV) expense ratio in 2025 remains ultra-low at just 0.03%, meaning investors pay only $3 annually for every $10,000 invested.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Does the iShares Core S&P 500 ETF IVV pay a dividend?</summary>
        <p>Yes, IVV pays a dividend derived from the underlying companies in the S&P 500 index. The yield generally tracks the broad market, typically hovering around 1.1% to 1.3%.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How often are dividends paid on IVV?</summary>
        <p>IVV distributes its dividends to shareholders on a quarterly basis, usually in March, June, September, and December.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is IVV better than SPY for expense ratio?</summary>
        <p>Yes, IVV's expense ratio of 0.03% is lower than SPY's expense ratio of 0.09%, making IVV slightly more cost-effective for long-term buy-and-hold investors.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What companies are in the IVV ETF?</summary>
        <p>IVV holds the same 500 large-cap U.S. companies that make up the S&P 500 Index, including major technology, healthcare, and financial sector leaders.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    function initIvvCalculator() {
      const container = document.getElementById('calcContainer');
      if (!container || container.dataset.initialized === 'true') return;

      const sharesInput = document.getElementById('shares');
      const priceInput = document.getElementById('sharePrice');
      const yieldInput = document.getElementById('yield');
      const expInput = document.getElementById('expRatio');

      const valueOutput = document.getElementById('totalValue');
      const feeOutput = document.getElementById('feeAmount');
      const netOutput = document.getElementById('netIncome');

      if (!sharesInput || !priceInput || !yieldInput || !expInput || !valueOutput || !feeOutput || !netOutput) return;

      function updateCalc() {
        const shares = parseFloat(sharesInput.value) || 0;
        const price = parseFloat(priceInput.value) || 0;
        const yieldPct = parseFloat(yieldInput.value) || 0;
        const expPct = parseFloat(expInput.value) || 0;

        const totalValue = shares * price;
        const grossIncome = totalValue * (yieldPct / 100);
        const fees = totalValue * (expPct / 100);
        const netIncome = grossIncome - fees;

        valueOutput.textContent = '$' + totalValue.toFixed(2);
        feeOutput.textContent = '-$' + fees.toFixed(2);
        netOutput.textContent = '$' + netIncome.toFixed(2);
      }

      sharesInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalc);
      priceInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalc);
      yieldInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalc);
      expInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalc);

      container.dataset.initialized = 'true';
    }

    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initIvvCalculator);
    document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', initIvvCalculator);
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    th, td { padding: 0.75rem 1rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    th { font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.85rem; text-transform: uppercase; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
